# <type>: <subject> (max 50 characters)

# Body: Explain *what* and *why* (not *how*). Wrap at 72 characters.


# Footer: Reference issues, breaking changes, etc.


# ==============================================================================
# Commit Message Guidelines
# ==============================================================================
#
# Type (choose one):
#   feat:     New feature
#   fix:      Bug fix
#   docs:     Documentation only changes
#   style:    Code style changes (formatting, missing semicolons, etc.)
#   refactor: Code change that neither fixes a bug nor adds a feature
#   perf:     Performance improvement
#   test:     Adding or updating tests
#   build:    Changes to build system or dependencies
#   ci:       Changes to CI configuration
#   chore:    Other changes that don't modify src or test files
#   revert:   Revert a previous commit
#
# Subject line:
#   - Use imperative mood ("Add feature" not "Added feature")
#   - Don't capitalize first letter
#   - No period at the end
#   - Max 50 characters
#
# Body:
#   - Separate from subject with blank line
#   - Wrap at 72 characters
#   - Explain what and why, not how
#   - Can use bullet points (- or *)
#
# Footer:
#   - Reference issues: "Closes #123", "Fixes #456"
#   - Note breaking changes: "BREAKING CHANGE: description"
#
# Examples:
#   feat: add user authentication system
#   fix: resolve memory leak in data processor
#   docs: update API documentation for v2.0
#   refactor: simplify error handling logic
#
# Good commit message example:
#
#   feat: add 1Password integration to direnv
#
#   Enables automatic loading of secrets from 1Password when entering
#   directories. Supports .oprc file for dedicated secrets and falls
#   back to .env with op:// references.
#
#   - Checks for op CLI and authentication
#   - Processes op:// references line by line
#   - Provides layout_op and layout_env_op functions
#
#   Closes #42
#
# ==============================================================================
